<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1384969" src="https://i2.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/Lekan.png?resize=640%2C342&#038;ssl=1" alt="COVID-19, Lekoil" width="640" height="342" srcset="https://i2.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/Lekan.png?w=855&amp;ssl=1 855w, https://i2.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/Lekan.png?resize=300%2C160&amp;ssl=1 300w, https://i2.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/Lekan.png?resize=768%2C410&amp;ssl=1 768w, https://i2.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/Lekan.png?resize=58%2C31&amp;ssl=1 58w, https://i2.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/Lekan.png?resize=260%2C139&amp;ssl=1 260w, https://i2.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/04/Lekan.png?resize=200%2C107&amp;ssl=1 200w" sizes="(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px" data-recalc-dims="1" /> Lekoil, an AIM-listed indigenous company has approved the immediate and accelerated implementation of the company’s General and Administrative (G&A) cost-reduction measures due to the significant drop in oil prices. Lekoil said that these measures were targeting an annual reduction of $8 million or at least 40 per cent in G&A costs, which is inclusive of a reduction in staff numbers. The company has already started the immediate execution of these measures, which will be completed within the next four to six weeks. According to Lekoil, production from Otakikpo field for the rest of this year will be unaffected by these measures. The company also said in the announcement that the payment of $2 million to Optimum Petroleum, the operator of the OPL 310 License off Nigeria, to cover the portion of sunk costs and consent fees had been completed. The sum was set to be paid on or before March 20. Lekoil’s CEO, Mr Lekan Akinyanmi, said: “We have kept our commitments on our world-class asset, OPL 310, despite the detrimental effects of the COVID-19 pandemic on the global economy and the subsequent fall in oil price. “With the implementation of our cost reduction measures, we believe we are in a good position to navigate this challenging period.” Vanguard Why we cut production — Lekoil By Dayo Johnson There are strong indications that the COVID-19 is affecting oil firms, leading to a sharp drop in oil demand as a result of storage for produced crude. In a statement, Chairman, Forum of Oil and Gas Managers in Nigeria, Philips Martins,… April 26, 2020 In "News" Nigeria's indigenous oil and gas exploration and production company, Lekoil, said it has reached an agreement with Optimum Petroleum Development Company, the Operator of the OPL 310 License, on deferring the company’s financial and operational obligations due in February 2020. January 24, 2020 In "Business" By Udeme Akpan LEKOIL, the oil and gas exploration and production company with a focus on Nigeria and other West African nations has secured $184 million to finance the appraisal drilling and initial development programme activities on the Ogo field within Oil Prospecting Lease, OPL 310. In a statement sent… January 2, 2020 In "Business"